Eating children suffering from obesity: No breakfast and sausages for dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight; while 9% of schoolchildren are overweight, 5% are obese.
According to the latest study, children suffering from obesity usually come from families who lead an unhealthy lifestyle.
We again see the importance of the environment and behavior patterns that accompany a person for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausages appear on the tables of children suffering from obesity, almost twice as often as in families with children who have a normal weight.
More than 19% of obese children ate fries at dinner on the eve of a survey related to an educational event called Obesity is not a coincidence.
Moreover, families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports. This, however, applies to most families of modern schoolchildren - only 15% of children said that their parents find time for sports at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last school year, with almost 900 elementary school students from all over Bohemia participating.
The Obesity event was not an accident for the second year in a row, with the support of insurance company V<0xC5><0xA1>eobecná zdravni poji<0xC5><0xA1><0xC5><0xA5>ovna and company Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils in grades 4-8 have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and adequate sports activity are the main determinants that cause the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either excess weight or obesity.
"For example, only half of the respondents said they ate five times a day, on a breakfast-breakfast-lunch-breakfast-dinner schedule, which is one of the essential conditions for proper nutrition," the study concluded.
No lunch and sausages in the evening.
Experts warn that even such relative details as a regular family breakfast time are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school families eat breakfast together.
In most families, breakfast is served separately.
The worst discovery is that in every tenth family, people do not eat breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The study found that fried foods are more commonly consumed in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet soft drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40% of children regularly exercise, this figure has more than doubled - up to 15% - when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to prepare their own menu based on the proposed products and based on their tastes and preferences.
“Food preferences in Czech children aged 12-15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating.”
Their favorite food includes a large number of flour, meat and sweet dishes.
“Special anxiety is caused by the great popularity of sweet soft drinks,” the study concludes.
As the main dish, the pasta defeated the bird with a small upper hand.
However, the children showed virtually no interest in beans, fish and vegetable dishes.
Striving for a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also found that children are willing to change their eating habits provided they are provided with relevant information.
“Many of the study’s control group demonstrated a significant shift in preferences toward healthy eating when they filled out a questionnaire after completing the Obesity lecture – it’s not a coincidence,” the study said.
This was especially noticeable, for example, in the case of sweet soft drinks - more children began to prefer them just water.
In addition, as a main dish, children were more likely to celebrate birds and fish, limiting the number of sweet dishes and pastries.
