V Need for Speed: Escape takes place in America.
Oversight
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work due to a series of completely inappropriate and negligent mistakes.
The ambitions were met to some extent, but that doesn’t matter, because no one clearly wanted to do extra work.
Before the release of the new version with the subheading "Escape" was associated with great hopes.
It was expected to shift previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; demo versions indicated that the game would take a decent place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main character gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, the end result is much different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the overall impression is spoiled by a few unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So, in reality, this is not a mistake, but a manifestation of the inexplicable laziness of developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You become part of the story, the protagonist of which, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race across America.
You get in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your task is to get to New York first.
This idea has a few interesting features.
The route consists of ten stages, divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes place on its own route, individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
Therefore, there is no sense that the same thing happens all the time in the game.
Despite the fact that the schedule is at the same level as in the previous parts of the series, some tracks are nice to watch.
However, the game does not evoke strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, in the autumn suburbs or high in the snowy mountains is very pleasant.
In addition, the race from time to time brings to life an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you get into a sandstorm, which significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you need to be careful not to get under an avalanche.
The races are quite well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that’s enough.
For a while you are trying to outrun several rivals (essentially a regular race); then you are trying to improve time (a standard race with a timer); or you are competing with one opponent.
In addition, from time to time you run into the police, which complicates your task even more.
The components on the outside of the car are new.
It’s just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's nothing complicated.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (only three to be exact).
In fact, it turns out that it’s good for the game because this property doesn’t bother; considering all of the above, it’s one of the things that makes the game more fun.
The racing model follows in the footsteps of previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but it cannot be considered a drawback.
If you are looking for an imitation of real life, you will have to look elsewhere.
And yet this model of driving is very suitable for dynamic races, although you can find better options on the market.
So far, it's very good.
However, after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
You don’t expect complex changes and collisions from such a game, but if you don’t have any idea before you collide with an object, how your machine will behave, something is wrong.
Usually, bypassing or passing by cars in a dense flow, you sometimes slightly touch another machine. And yet sometimes in a practically similar situation, your machine starts to spin insanely.
Or it's just broken.
It’s not that important thanks to the restart system, but it’s enough to spoil the fun.
The restarts are arranged in such a way that if you crash or go far away from the track, the game returns you to the point where it stopped.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you will have to start the race from the beginning.
This is useful in case something doesn’t work out, but you can’t fully rely on it.
Sometimes reboots are not enough, and you have to learn a separate section of the race by heart.
An important disadvantage of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to be passed in a certain way, otherwise you just won’t fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian cars in a certain place in the same configuration regardless of whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see your opponent easily passing between two cars moving in the opposite direction, while when you are there, the cars are already positioned so that you need to either bypass them or set the speed.
It doesn’t matter when you’re around them; everything is arranged so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Rivals have other advantages.
During the game you discover several places where, regardless of the time, the same opponent overtakes you in the same place.
This is especially evident at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you go in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent has to stand in front of you no matter what.
The fact is that when he drives in front of you, it worsens your overview, which leads to one or more accidents on this site.
You can understand the attempt to make the game more interesting and full of adrenaline, but it is so obvious that it quickly begins to cause irritation.
It’s a pity because despite the simple driving model, the game is entertaining and sometimes so eventful that you don’t have time to pay attention to what’s going on around you.
It doesn’t matter what you don’t miss – a concept with fifty unique tracks, a sequence of races or something else.
The idea of changing cars during a race is unusual.
You need to track the fillings along the way, because it is on them that your car can change, despite the fact that in most cases the one you already have is quite enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars are for straight sections of the highway; and exotic super-sportsmen for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain tracks.
The main story mode is closely related to the challenge mode; these are races on individual sections that you will learn in the course of the game.
Here you win both medals and points for your personal business, common to the challenges and story modes.
Many possibilities are available to achieve a higher level of driving: starting from cars and ending with profile data.
In addition, the profile is associated with the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares the results you achieved with the results of other players, and provides communication with the public.
Here’s another drawback that’s hard to understand; this is an example from the last race in a sequence.
You and your car get into a subway tunnel (we’ll assume that’s the case), where you run on rails in the dark (we’ll assume that’s the case).
Your speedometer shows figures from 150 to 200 km/h (we’ll assume that’s the case) when suddenly a subway train hits you in the back, turning your car into a heap of scrap.
For a few days, our editors have been discussing whether, at the time of making the game, no one really thought for a second, or if its creators really think of us as such idiots.
The technical component of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression of the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although it’s a pity that at some critical moments, the quality of the recording, sometimes quite severely, decreases.
This is especially true for incidents with a large number of participants, where a good record wouldn’t help you either.
The sound is fine; the soundtrack is for the amateur.
In order to please the broadest possible youth audience, the soundtrack has 'compositions of different styles'; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
Need for Speed: Escape is a bit of a mess.
If the game had avoided clearly unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
In any case, the game leaves a feeling of incompleteness.
Of course, it’s a good entertainment, but be prepared for the fact that the shortcomings will blind you like an airport spotlight.
