Ambassador to the EU Vicenova:
The Czechs have a reputation for being unfriendly and skeptical of the euro.
"The Treaty of Lisbon has caused considerable disagreements between individual organizations."
“I didn’t expect such a terrible war.”
"It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes, calms down and all players will get used to their new roles," EU Ambassador Milena Vicenova began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
She proved how much she adheres to her motto "Clear and Open about Europe" in the first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and the relationship between them so simply and clearly that many lecturers from the CU Law School would be envious.
Moreover, Vicenova commended the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, critics said he was an ordinary gray office mouse who can't play any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he handled his role."
“He is a person who can listen to twenty-seven member countries at the same time, who is great at communicating with them and who has a clear idea of which side the EU needs to develop.”
She explained her new position as a representative for international relations and security as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? What number should I call?"; i.e. as an important step towards the unification and greater transparency of the Union's policy towards countries such as China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheeses.
Vitsenova continued to focus on a program that is key to the EU in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech Presidency a successful one last year.
The Czechs were dealing with the impending financial crisis; they overcame this crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership summit.
She said the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon that had caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
Czech representatives in the EU are currently very busy.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis caused the ongoing fermentation.
In addition, it is necessary to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is very difficult given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support and which will receive less; all these issues are in the forthcoming agenda.
The ambassador recalled the key slogans she brought to Brussels: “About Europe, in a language that can be understood”.
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that no one understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheese varieties?
It is also going to make more effective use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organisations.
A multi-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador argues that the Czechs are considered to be Eurosceptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than positive sides of things.
She wants more representatives of the Czech Republic to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that this is due to several factors: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time, with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful presidency of the Czech Republic, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary, and a Slovak joins us, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, on what occasion is the Visegrad Group again?' and he's not even happy with that.
In the future, the Union of Vitsenov expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policies of the member states.
Compared to the new European Federation, it considers the idea of a two-speed, if not multiple-speed Europe more realistic.
“We have countries both inside and outside the Eurozone.”
"We have the Schengen area, and we already have the institution of enhanced cooperation."
“For the first time, it was said that countries that want must unite, while those that don’t can stay aside.”
“The number of such institutions will grow; it will really be a two-speed Europe,” Vicenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in advancing the rule that all issues pertaining to the whole EU should be discussed by all the participating countries, not just those belonging to the eurozone.
Brand's History:
The IBM innovator enters the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find a word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest one is likely to be “long-lasting.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The longevity of the company was established by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson, Senior.
He believed in his motto that many world problems can be easily solved if people want to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a constant move to the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, although it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first 100 years, this has allowed us to transform technology, business and company.
In the next 100 years, we hope to achieve even more,” said Samuel J. Palmizano, current CEO of the company.
Complicated system
