IBM's Story: From a Cheese Knife to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago. Its original name "Computing, Tabulation, Recording Corporation" was quite complex.
It took the name IBM in 1924. Originally, this was the name of the brand used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundations of IBM's future were laid by the merger of four companies, whose history begins in the 1880s.
They possessed technologies such as the legendary "table clock", i.e. clocks that record the time when employees come and go from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Runlet Flint, who also chaired the board of trustees of the company until 1930.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the director of the company, to help him run the company.
Then the CEO pushed the founder of IBM into the shadows – Watson’s ideas remain the basis of an unwavering corporate culture and individuality.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and sale of various business equipment – from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company's massive expansion into all continents began.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his place in the chair was taken by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both employees and IBM computers helped NASA control spaceflight — to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 — man’s flight to the Moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM Line System/360.
The classic PC, which defined computer standards at the time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computer production to Chinese company Lenovo, simultaneously acquiring consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus focusing entirely on high-value consulting and services.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its goal is to use technology wisely in areas where it has not yet been planned, and to improve the road situation and urban governance.
In the field of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
IBM’s traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM established its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also manages a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters of Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, where a world-class research group on speech recognition also operates.
