Dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed to work in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was strictly restricted, travel agencies of the time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, on holiday Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which resulted in significant restrictions on travel by Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was required; otherwise, an individual trip was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but it was either necessary to stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or to have "good friends" in the agency.
And that's not all.
Currency authorization was required for travel to the West and was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without currency authorization it was impossible to obtain money (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the appearance of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit persists to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus survived a real revolution.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are no longer aware of is that until 1989 we were not able to freely visit the most popular Croatia nowadays, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the visa requirement for neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, triggering a huge wave of short trips, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of traveling to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time lacked a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring their own food (canned food, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown. After decades, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income increased, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared with the past, air travel has now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to book wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit virtually all developed countries of the world except the United States. This made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000. Large demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter flights from the Czech Republic will depart to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, occurred in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. repealed the requirement to obtain a visa for Czech tourists. Our country thus forever joined the most developed countries of the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15,000 SEK per person during their holiday abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
