How could this happen?
If you ask Swiss banks, they will say that the problem is mainly the size of UBS.
Two of Switzerland’s three largest banks merged into one large group in June 1998.
A bank was formed that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger, and a bank that continued to grow.
This was also helped by the fact that the two banks that formed UBS complemented each other. One was a wealthy but progressive bank specializing in asset management in Zurich; the other was not so wealthy but much more internationalized.
Internationalized investment bankers suddenly gained access to a large amount of money that they could use to spin the omnipotent wheel.
Two names are linked to UBS growth: Peter Wolffley, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I’ve always believed that Wolffley and Ospel are the team of dreams,” says bank analyst Hans Geiger.
“Wolfley, an outstanding intellectual, modest and deeply understanding of models and statistics, and Ospel with his inner instincts, went all the way up, starting with an intern at the bank.”
But Ospel eventually relied on Wolffley.
And Wolffley could have made a critical mistake. "He thought his models were a reality," says Geiger.
"It's tragic."
Maybe it's tragic.
Pride precedes defeat.
UBS employees remember well the meetings of board members, at which Wolffley always repeated the same slogan - to move Goldman Sachs.
