UBS was the largest player in currency and government securities trading.
Authorized management consultants, however, pointed to a weakness. By the parameter that in banking terminology is called "permanent income", UBS was far behind the largest banks.
UBS has failed in U.S. mortgage products.
To close the hole, UBS got involved in an adventure that almost cost him his life.
In an effort to grow, the bank itself and the hedge fund it founded invested in U.S. substandard securities.
This evolved into a large mechanism that combined securities based on U.S. mortgages and sold them on – continuing to bear the risks themselves.
Even when other banks have long been looking for a way out of this process, UBS has not stopped.
“UBS bought it until the summer of 2007, when the U.S. real estate market was already on fire,” says bank analyst Geiger.
The higher the growth, the deeper the fall.
One manager after another had to leave as attempts to put the bank in order turned out to be more difficult than it seemed at first.
Posts at UBS have become a children’s game with chairs and to this day remain unreliable.
Anyone who heads this huge bank faces an almost impossible task.
He must find a strategy for a bank that has turned its back on all existing business models.
Geiger’s banking analyst already has an idea – to give up investment banking, focus on asset management, and forget about his Swiss roots.
