Mass murders – the human dimension
A tense and very good new book by Peter Englund, Beauty and Sorrow: The Personal History of World War I, begins with a long list of actors whose heart is frozen.
Here’s a tip on how to read on: carefully trim this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will meet these people very closely as Mr. Englund narrates, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon in those moments when, as one of these men and women, you will fall off the road and be lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he wrote now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as “work on anti-history.”
There are few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, clever journalists or discussions of tactics and combat equipment.
It's not so much a book about what it was, he explains, as "a book about what it looked like." It's about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and the state of mind."
The book “Beauty and Sorrow” brought together the experience of 20 military years of more or less understated men and women, on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and servants.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses an arm or a leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives flash here like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some at this time are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is also an amendment to the idea that World War I was only a heavy trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skillfully gives the panorama of other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are beehives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unresolved problem is the tsetse flies.
This is an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War covers the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling like smokeless powder.
When a canon is heard nearby, and you are a woman and are at home with children, will you stay in place or run away?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening and why it is necessary to fight in this war.
