On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to committing a mass murder in Norway in July that killed 77 people, appeared at his first open trial.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was far from alone on the net: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack behind his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
It's easy - you just have to go to Facebook.
“We realized that it was easy to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on European cyber-populism by the British DEMOS Research Center.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to highlight the necessary demographic group with scientific accuracy — which marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team discovered half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then pushed them to show an ad, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad offered the user a survey that asked questions about their level of education, their attitude to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – even without leaving the office.
“It’s a whole new way of doing research,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not as striking: right-wing online supporters are mostly male young people dissatisfied with immigration.
But unexpectedly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends that are expressed in likes, posts on the wall, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-actual information” is triggering a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles titled a site by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you can’t access on the street with a notebook.
“In the past, if you wanted to question people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to join the party, and they would never accept you,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you are addressing them directly.”
Others say that with the help of this site it would be possible to identify and investigate social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Meghan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken feats on Facebook were significantly more at risk for alcoholism than students who remained silent about it.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as their hostel mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drunk statuses.
“You can’t solve the problem without revealing it,” said Dimitri Hristokis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify children at risk that we would not otherwise have detected."
Facebook also constantly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The data processing team of the site has processed statistics on the status of relationships and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in mid-2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (mainly using information that only they have access to - cyber-liberty champions have long insisted on the fact that the site should make its extensive call.
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for the ability to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away from you, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined norms for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about what a researcher can look at their profiles,” says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using publicly available student pages on Facebook.
"As far as they could imagine, it was just between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline there is no guarantee that the object of research is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user’s page is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selvin said.
That’s why, despite years of technology research, Selvin thinks notebooks and pens are still the best research tools you can use.
“Nothing can replace getting out into the real world and communicating with real people,” he says.
