7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview Showed at the Theatre This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans can count as the biggest discovery in a newly discovered interview, which was recalled in anticipation of previews in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was of course a designer, a dreamer and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business leaders suffered from the "disease of thinking that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] a huge amount of work from a great product separates the idea."
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the TV series Triumph of the Nerds about the emergence of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique long conversation.
By then, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he was already working for his new computer company NeXT in anticipation of the mass development of the Internet.
While a small portion of Kringley's interviews were used in the Nerds, he says the originals of the interviews disappeared during transportation.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full VHS copy was found in the director’s garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: A Lost Interview, which is released at Landmark Theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusually prepared here to expose his technological philosophy and business strategy.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different points during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers—thoughts of 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to say the least.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by Kringle’s questions, forcing him to move more quickly to issues or phenomena of greater importance.
In the pre-Pixar era, iPods and iPhones, the Lost Interview is something sinisterly prophetic when Jobs assesses what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
It’s one thing to read about Jobs’ post-mortem assessments, but there’s something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, an alarming dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Soon after he said everything here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven significant findings of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"All the time in business, I've been asking, 'Why are you doing this?' And the answers you're always getting, 'Oh, that's just how it's done.'
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks very deeply in business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues to describe in detail his attempts to streamline reporting at Apple.
Disturbed by the way of recording expenses, often starting with “standard expenses” that were taken from the ceiling and then tailored with “clarification,” he created an automated structure that ensured that they would be able to track business expenses down to the smallest detail.
A joke about the Pope:
Jobs talks in detail about the "blue box" he crafted with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and call long distances for free.
Much has been written about the device before, but Jobs' euphoria here when describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box using a phone-machine, ordering a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
“We’ve covered the globe half a dozen times, and you were yelling at the phone machine, and it went into the next phone machine a minute later,” Jobs says with a smile.
“We were young, and all we learned was that we could craft something that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us knew a little bit, but we could master the little thing that could control the big thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple could ever have come out without it.
Jobs goes on to describe in detail one famous outing that he and Wozniak practically coped with by calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking the Pope on the phone, trying to copy Henry Kissinger.
When different members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to talk to an American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was raised to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and Bill Hewlett’s cold calling):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to assemble the frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“It had a strong impact on me, it was the only company I saw at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer".
He was the size of a suitcase, he had a small monitor with an electron beam tube, and I fell in love with it.
I used to drive to HP as a teenager and spin around that car and write programs for it.
About Improvised Innovation:
In several places the interview Jobs talks about the invention of new products in the summer.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of circuit boards, a buyer asked him to assemble an entire computer.
Working only 30 days on credit, he had to think about both assembly and delivery of ready-made devices.
Later at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he faced while developing a computer mouse:
“I remember the fierce controversy... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to collect a mouse that would cost $300] and I was fed up with it, and I went out and found a designer.”
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we were able to collect for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
Some of the companies that are losing energy:
Long before he led Apple’s revival, Jobs predicted exactly how many industry leaders would go wrong in their vision of the situation and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make a better copy or printer, and what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who ultimately come to run the companies, and the people making the product are pushed out of the decision-making arena.
The genius of the product that led to this monopolistic position is displaced by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products – the required skill.
This is what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could take over the entire information technology industry.
It could have been ten times bigger, it could have been Microsoft in the 90s...
They were defeated by victory.
About innovation as a form of art:
“A great idea is separated from a great product by a huge amount of skillful work ... when you unfold a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You will learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises you need to make – some things you won’t be able to make electrons, glass, robots, or factories.
You need to keep 5,000 ideas in mind — these concepts — connecting them all together...
Ultimately, it’s all about the taste – it’s all about trying to express yourself in the best way people have ever produced, and later – trying to bring it into what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've always been ashamed to steal great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh famous was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to become the best information technology specialists in the world.
If it weren’t for information technology, they would have done amazing things in other areas.
