Climate change has slowed the economy.
During the first year of Mario Lopez’s rule in Sinaloa, unemployment and the illegal labor market increased, foreign funding declined and the economy weakened.
2011 is the year that will enter the economic history of Sinaloa as related to the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, also called the year of change, which gave rise to great hopes for the development of the economy, but given the unfavorable climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth, but there was a decline in economic development.
The low temperatures in February have not only resulted in loss of millions for the agricultural sector, but they have limited the potential for growth of the state economy, causing a decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent overall in the first half of the year, mainly due to a historic decline of 31.16 percent in other sectors of agriculture, which is expected to increase the growth of the economy.
According to a report on areas affected by frost provided by the Council of Mexico for Sustainable Rural Development, 835.582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 per cent were affected entirely, and the remaining 21.07 per cent were partially affected.
The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state of 18.000 before. according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, in the first three quarters of September was recorded an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March 55.053 inhabitants of Sinaloa were unemployed, before 5.
Decreased liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is plagued by many factors, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly by actions taken in public policy.
“What we’re seeing now is an increase in unemployment, which is linked to a number of factors, including the loss of market liquidity in order to limit the resources imposed by a law that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, because people who illegally own dollars, he said, it’s not easy to work with them.
Detained Immigration
Lopez Cervantes said that there is also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad in the United States has been limited, primarily due to difficulties with entry, and in the second - since, once they have entered, they already face a lot of difficulties in finding a job result, so a group of people stays in and requires jobs.
Violation of formal requirements
The analysis of Sinaloa’s labor market is getting worse if we take into account the large number of violations that prevail in the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the active population of the state works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and registration violations, another reminder about working in the state is low wages; the state has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,352 pesos, much lower than the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the high rate of unemployment in 2011, the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the last 10 years was recorded, according to the Ministry of Finance, from January to July, the state FDI amounted to $ 630.697.
For its part, the State Government’s Ministry of Economic Development recorded only 17.280,000 pesos of investments during the year, which were mainly incurred by service companies.
Debt
Against the backdrop of the economic downturn, the state government requested in July during the state congress approval of a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be used for investments in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, at the local level only 2,600 million pesos were approved by the state, and by November the economy was not expected to exceed.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez demonstrates the lack of opportunities of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that during 2011, there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year has been really low, it takes a lot of work to restore the positions lost this year, in 2012, we have to double our efforts, we have not been able to reconcile the efforts of everyone and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be better for us."
The slowdown of the economy
Lopez Loredo said that events such as early frosts have halted the state’s economy this year and its efficiency and growth have been limited.
"The low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that is not becoming fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows us to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and therefore at the end of the year we close it below our expectations," he said.
Revision of direction
Theodore Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said the state needs to continue its most dynamic manufacturing activity.
“In general, we found that we were working on this, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Upcoming work
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining a future direction in order to better guide the government’s efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has demonstrated progress in its own way of conducting public policy.
"There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved and that I can say that some work has been done and I think the government is aware that there is much more to be done," he said.
