The court will approve the "transition to digital television" in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has undergone in recent years.
The Supreme Court has rejected constitutional claims put forward by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which postpones the so-called “transition to digital television” from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to override it have not been cast.
A minority of four ministers, including President Juan Silva Mesa, said President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers by issuing a decree detailing the steps to transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were dismissed due to the absence of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television program is a right enshrined in the law by the Federal Commission on Telecommunications (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the law.
Only Salvador, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the meeting of ministers, it was also decided to reject the demand of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive cannot determine by general rules the measures to be prepared by the state administration.
“I also don’t think that if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body,” and reminded that planning public policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the management of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years has led to better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Delaying the transition, he said, would mean deferring the benefits of digital transformation, which includes meeting societal needs, which has a not only technical dimension, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic management, includes a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into the state executive power."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and did so with the help of the executive branch, despite the presence of highly specialized technical institutions.
From this it cannot be concluded that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competences of Congress, ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
