The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the Italian president to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic catastrophe and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive body will take its positions.
Monty said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say explicitly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The structure is now well outlined," he said.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy has been battling a political and financial crisis that has brought the size of their debt to a critical level.
The administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Under pressure from Monti to rush, unstable markets set BTP Italy’s bond yield by 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be rescued.
Emma Marchegalia, the leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after meeting with Monti: “We have said that we will actively support this government.”
We believe that this government is Italy’s last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monty’s chances of success were largely based on the support of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts should lead to a good outcome,” Angelino Alfano, the secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
Support for the LDP, Italy’s largest party, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the technocratic government majority that Monti is forming.
The Parliamentary Support
The new Monty government should have strong parliamentary support for reforms that will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts can lead to a new and destructive attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has stepped up the pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
Monty began consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He will finish the series of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italy’s debt value has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescuing Italy with a <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.8 billion in government debt would be too much for the eurozone’s modern financial defenders.
