The quintet included the country in a tour in honor of the twentieth anniversary of his career
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true.
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to give one of the best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
There have been more than 20 years of waiting, but the band says it’s also a dream come true for them to play in this country.
This was the assertion of bassist and founder, Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is on the territory of South America as part of a 20-year tour and will make its only stop in Central America on Sunday, 20th.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the Los Angeles team The X and the local group Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full decryption of which is available online at The Nation.
For your Costa Rican fans, is it a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica? Do you know what your fans are experiencing?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us, too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far everything is going well.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica once – on vacation, it’s a beautiful country and I think we can stay there for a few days.
We are very happy to bring our music there.
I ask about it because there is some commitment to the band; fans live in tension in the days before the concert.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we regret that it took us so long to get here.
Some people, waiting for your concert, treat it as the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a bit of tension to your visit?
“Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the past 21 years have taken place over the past two weeks.
We had some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope this has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle when it comes to these two things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you find out about Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, as well as Mexico, these are great places for surfing, this is how we learned about it, from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you can say that you did a great show with a lot of songs.
What do you plan to do in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there before, we have no limits on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible with a variety of songs; we will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a wide variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does that work?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven’t played for a while, it keeps us in the tone and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and so I think it makes it more interesting for people.
This tour marks 20 years of your career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yeah, sure.
“First, I don’t think any of us could ever have imagined that we’d be in a rock band and that we’ve been doing this for more than 20 years makes it like a dream.
We are delighted with our success and we are very excited that we can continue to create music together.
We all love each other and love to make music.
We are happy to travel to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
For us, everything is going very well.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the bloom of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We are good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s great when movement grows out of a group of friends, and that’s unusual.
From time to time, one group appears from one city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we’re happy to be friends with all of them and it’s an honor to be part of the sound of Seattle that has turned out.
It’s also very strange that a group like yours stays together and in the same band for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than there are many bands.
First, I think we're lucky we're still alive, and second, we take care of others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to this, musical pathways have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other’s music, and it couldn’t have been better.
Your attitude to the word glory was not easy; but thanks to your success you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier to find a balance.
We take care not to be too long on tour because it’s easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what it did without deciding to be famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
