He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
Among the first to come to mind are Geiser Butler, John Entvisl, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in keeping the grunge relevant despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of bands that I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came along at the same time, and if it’s important now, I think it’s great because it’s music that’s worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making music now better than ever before.
At first your music was darker, but now it has become more positive.
How would you explain this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that may seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, although they can sound a little positive.
From both of them when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs are very dark.
I think when you’re growing up and there’s been some kind of trauma in your life and you’ve lost a family member or friend, these events begin to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
