Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group formed by the most highly developed and developing countries, and has, in fact, an agreement with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the conclusion of tax-exchange agreements to leave this “gray list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, made up of countries that do not enjoy international standards of tax cooperation.
