MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social Protection Leads Study to Find Obesity Gene in Children and Young People; Supported by IPN Experts
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which is called the protocol "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescent" that will provide counting of signs associated with overweight.
In his statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the National Medical Center’s 21st Century Specialized Hospital, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers had gathered.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to take part, going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children will be conducted every Saturday, from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol was started at the sports center in Quautemoque (in the west of Mexico City), and since October 8 the events are held at the sports center in Nesaualcoyotle (east of Mexico City).
Once the goal of attracting between 500 and 600 children is reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (South Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (North Mexico).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, World Diabetes Day will be celebrated, and the main goal is to gather 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14 with the permission of parents and under their supervision to fill in individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and a history of familial hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose levels, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be conducted.
Cruz López said that the study reflects the concerns of health professionals about the worrying weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that there was an increase in just 6 years: in the case of boys, 77 percent were obese, in the case of girls, 47 percent; in terms of excess weight, there was also a significant increase," said MSSI specialist.
He said that the validity of the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, the Mexican is 65 percent offspring of American Indians, 30 percent offspring of Europeans, and five percent offspring of Africans, and this condition affected the genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the genetics of obesity are mainly due to the body’s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories), and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for participants is a comprehensive assessment of children, which can reveal whether they have any degree of excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is handled with all confidentiality, the doctors pass it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that need to be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV, and using transport at short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to the high calorie intake, that is, the increased consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
UNAM asphalt will be able to avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM chemical faculty, has developed polymer-modified bitumen to produce a blend of the best quality, environmentally and temperature resistant.
If the signals sent by the road cover were paid attention, then it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area in the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Naher, a researcher at the chemical faculty of UNAM, and adds that if the process of construction and maintenance is insufficient.
In his lecture, The Technological View of the Pit, read within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and hence counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of the oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which have a high molecular mass, called asphaltites, and others have a low molecular mass, called maltenes, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscosity.
The viscous behavior of bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it maintains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes crumbly.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but varies throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, a specialist in chemical engineering said.
The scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which consists of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the topmost layers is the bitumen, composed of small stones dropped into the bitumen and then squeezed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is submerged in bitumen.
When driving vehicles and exerting effort, this helps forces to distribute very well on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt coating, he added, is placed the last layer, which is called a layer of wear, which is made of fine stone, in fact sand also immersed in the asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the transport wheels, it should have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
Being part of the road covering that will receive and disseminate these efforts, the layer of wear also requires proper thickness, and it is necessary to take into account the material from which it is made.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the soil is raw, the water penetrates the coating and it is difficult to get out of it, this causes the softening of all layers of the coating and, therefore, the formation of pits.
When pits are formed, he said, the first layer of wear is worn and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantly, this is a process that should be paid attention at the first signs of ongoing repair programs.
A member of the National Research System explained that transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating should always be associated with transport load and it is necessary to ensure that this requirement is met to prevent frequent occurrence of holes.
Rafael Herrera said that much still needs to be studied and done about bitumen, for example, bitumen emulsions that are already on the market in other countries and even help to repair pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
