“The way these two organizations are using and the reports of the secret services show that they are actively cooperating,” he said, without going into details.
Paris seems to have come to similar conclusions.
An investigation into the kidnapping of two French men in Niger in January revealed two linkages.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Leocourt and Vincent Delori, apparently were killed the next day along with several of the kidnappers during an operation carried out by French special forces.
Among the debris left after the operation, French and Nigerian investigators found several phone SIM cards belonging to the terrorists.
The Axis of Terror
The analysis of the calls pointed to several interlocutors in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers; one points to a Nigerian who has long lived in Maidiguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other points to a person allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we certainly have to wait for more reliable evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“It has been known for many years that the cult receives financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active,” said Kunle Amuvo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this support has become increasingly evident in the actions and statements of Boko Haram and its methods, which now include the use of suicide bombers and increasingly complex explosive devices of the same type used by Aqmi.
The international community, led by Washington, is now putting pressure on Abuja to draw attention to the problems created by Boko Haram.
The fact is that the Nigerian authorities have traditionally regarded this group as a community of enlightened people who are not of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maidiguri at a mosque, a school, and under the imam-fundamentalist Mohamed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means "Western education is a sin" on the house - preaches the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization has achieved rapid success.
It is politicized and demands strict adherence to Sharia law, and its activists have begun the fight against the wicked central government.
It is mainly targeted at churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active in carrying out numerous attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction, as usual, is uncompromising.
The army blockaded the city and left 800 dead.
Mohamed Yusuf, taken alive, was killed in prison.
Now the sect is radicalizing and will go beyond its northern wings.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an action that killed 80 people in Jos, and then another one in Abuja.
In June, in Abuja, Boko Haram organized the first suicide attack on a fortified police headquarters.
In August, the local representation of the United Nations will be their first international goal.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which runs from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, now worries all security experts.
Today, when Aqmi has strengthened in Mali and Niger, and Somalis from al-Shabaab are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram poses a new threat to the continent.
Last week, during a conversation with Presidents Goodluck, Jonathan Allen Juppé warned of the dangers of Boko Haram and expressed readiness to share all available information.
The world as seen by Republican presidential candidates
With regard to China, Iran and Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Kane and Rick Perry compete in simplicity and incompetence.
Can a crisis-weakened America lead a complex world with simple, or more precisely, simplistic ideas?
If you listen to Republican presidential candidates, voters could believe it.
For a few days now, Mitt Romney, Herman Kane, Rick Perry and others have been multiplying the loud but detailless statements on foreign policy that have traditionally been the strong side of Republicans.
The slogans concerning China, Iran and aid to Israel are often confused with each other.
Mitt Romney, who has the best chance of being promoted from the “Old Good Party”, threatened to file a complaint against the Chinese at the WTO and accuse them of “manipulating their currency is a sensitive topic for America, annoyed by the migration of entire industries to Asia.”
Even worse, if it leads to a trade war, he said.
John Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate who knows complex foreign policy, has not been able to overcome a position that encourages emotions.
He called for a firm but constructive dialogue with Beijing (the current position of Obama).
But Huntsman, who remains at the bottom of the ratings, remained unheard of.
In the style of Reagan
Romney has also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
“If I am chosen, I will stop Iran,” he said.
“If Obama is re-elected, they’ll have a bomb.”
He also pledged to step up military assistance to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to deliver on his promises to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Kane, second in the ranking of candidates, demonstrated discouraging ignorance of the cases.
He recently called for confronting the Chinese military threat because Beijing is trying to achieve nuclear power – obviously not knowing that China has possessed it since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and seeks military strikes on Iran, says he is ready to use the U.S. military in Mexico against drug cartels.
Recourse to torture of suspected terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also recommended by Kane, Perry and candidate Michelle Bachman.
All this is very far from the 2008 Republican candidate John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president respond that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They remind that Obama himself was a fan and that he had to lower his tone in the fight against terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the premature withdrawal of the “boys” from Iraq, on his tricks in Libya that brought him the reputation of a weak politician.
But the offensive is not so easy.
The population considers a positive balance of national security under Obama, who eliminated Ben Laden.
After Iraq, it does not believe in military interventions that tie in the sand.
And, claiming that America needs to be rebuilt economically in order to revive its leadership, Obama is right.
The North Stream, a new gateway for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North Stream pipeline, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly on the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is designed to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the performance of the orchestra and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Marthe Rutte together turned the symbolic valve controlling the Russian gas inflow into the Western European network.
According to the new pipeline, an additional 27.500 million cubic meters of gas will flow to Western Europe each year on the first pipeline of 1,224 km long, connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready at the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas equivalent to all of France’s consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it harder to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the heaviest moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop to compare the North Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin in order to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of supply.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
Russia has managed in less than five years to achieve its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
“This pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically connects us,” said François Fillon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Ljubljana, the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel locked in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to circumvent the minefields that remained from World War II.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also a need to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake with a weight equal to the weight of 242 Eiffel Towers, without gaps along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers rejected it because Sweden was not thrilled that the Russian state-owned company would forever settle off its shores.
“In the event of an accident, we will shut down the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
So, in case of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will leak into the air.
But this seems unlikely to designers who designed seams designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
The control of the gas pipeline will be carried out by a submarine robot pulling the ship for external monitoring, as well as an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is inserted into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by a flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second it gives accurate information about any metal deformation.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
The circulation of gas is carried out only at the expense of its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital, remains the leader.
The rest are the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Dutch Gasunie and the French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was commissioned to build and operate the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased this company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas is actually being transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for two pipelines.
GDF Suez’s investment will be around $240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay for their costs, because Gazprom assumes all the risks.
The pipeline leaves the Baltic Sea in Ljubljana on a sandy shore planted with coniferous trees.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the output terminal of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 6 million.
Moleskine brand notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste to the letter.
It has the scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
Moleskine notebook is easy to recognize on a rectangular black cover, on rubber, on yellowish-white pages, as if yellowed with time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, has decided to launch design notebooks for sale.
Maria Sebregondi, the company’s consultant at the time, took responsibility for launching a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique, moleskine - lacquered cotton fabric, used, for example, to cover scamaees.
It is claimed that this type of notebook is highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought into line with today’s taste the old and forgotten thing that was cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the managing brand at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales grew by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We have gone far from the production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish the profile of a typical buyer, because the notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student and a person of a free profession.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small towns and has been able to gain widespread fame.
“We have followed the spirit of time and this new need for letters, despite the emergence of email,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This characteristic cultural feature accompanies Moleskine's development; the brand recently organized an exhibition called "The Surrounding Road", where architects and artists demonstrated their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched covers with a leopard drawing on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Using its successes and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
A success that gave rise to envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was purchased by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which has entered a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week of disability employment begins today.
Despite the public charity policy initiated in 2005, unemployment among the disabled is still twice as high as the average, 19 per cent against 9 per cent for the general population.
Disappointing?
“No,” says Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for people with disabilities.
“In 15 years, significant progress has been made.”
“At that time, the unemployment rate was not two, but three times higher.”
“There is still a lot of work ahead.”
It must be said that there are still many barriers to employment for the disabled.
Among them, there are more elderly people: 37% over the age of 50 (17% on average).
They have a rather low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very prevalent, which is 85% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, all of these are criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are the essence of the problem,” said Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur Association on behalf of Cité found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “represented ordinary people in strollers or mentally or mentally handicapped.”
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the target of having 6% of disabled workers set out in a law passed in 1987.
The latest known figures for 2008 give a value of 2.6%.
“Today we’re about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that don’t comply with the law.
Evidence: The number of "taxable" organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which raised the tax, put a lot of pressure on the company,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects an increase in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with employees from 20 to 49 have disabled workers, compared to 82% of organizations with employees from 100 to 199.
